if allready you have the cluster and you want to connect t that cluster :

Check kubectl path:

	which kubectl

Expected:

/usr/local/bin/kubectl

or

/usr/bin/kubectl

Check Kubernetes config
	kubectl config view

Check current context
	kubectl config current-context

List contexts
	kubectl config get-contexts

Check kubeconfig environment variable
	echo $KUBECONFIG



Check if kubeconfig exists

Run:
	ls -la ~/.kube

Then:

	cat ~/.kube/config

If the file doesn't exist, that's okay—it means we need to create it.



Check whether your EKS cluster still exists

Run:

	aws eks list-clusters --region us-east-1

If the cluster exists

We'll regenerate the kubeconfig:

	aws eks update-kubeconfig \
 	 --region us-east-1 \
  	 --name <your-cluster-name>



